This paper deals with the computation of functions using discrete chemical reaction networks, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of computer science and chemistry. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science), which specifically deals with the application of computer science to scientific and engineering problems. The paper also involves the study of discrete mathematical structures (CRNs) and their properties, which makes cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) another likely sub-category. The use of CRNs for computation also involves control and system theory, which falls under cs.SY (Systems and Control). The paper also involves the study of the stability of CRN computation, which is related to information theory and communication, making cs.IT (Information Theory) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the study of the properties of functions that can be stably computed using CRNs, which is related to machine learning and pattern recognition, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category as well.
